# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-people-s-history-of-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The **Scottish devolution referendum of 1997** was a pre-legislative referendum held in Scotland on 11 September 1997 over whether there was support for the creation of a Scottish Parliament with devolved powers, and whether the Parliament should have tax-varying powers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The result was "Yes–Yes": a majority voted in favour of both proposals, and the Parliament was established following an election in 1999.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The referendum was a Labour Party manifesto commitment and was held in their first term in office after the 1997 general election, under the provisions of the Referendums (Scotland and Wales) Act 1997.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was the second referendum held in Scotland over the question of devolution, the first being in 1979, and is to date the only major referendum to be held in any part of the United Kingdom where voters were asked two questions in the same plebiscite.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] A referendum was held in 1979 under a Labour government which stipulated that a Scottish Assembly would come into being if the referendum had been supported by 50% of votes cast plus a controversial rule whereby at least 40% of the electorate had to vote in favour.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Although 51.6% voted in favour, this was only 32.9% of the electorate so the Assembly was not brought into being.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Shortly afterwards, the predominantly anti-devolution-led Conservative Party won the 1979 general election.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] That government put devolution to one side but it was a policy area that remained on the agenda of the Labour Party.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] A Campaign for a Scottish Assembly was formed afterwards to continue the campaign.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] They brought together a committee of "prominent Scots" who drafted the document "A Claim of Right for Scotland".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The "Claim" was published in 1988 and signed by most Scottish politicians, local councils, trade unions and churches.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was agreed to form a Scottish Constitutional Convention, made up of existing MPs and councillors.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Labour Party included the establishment of a Scottish Parliament in its manifesto for the 1997 general election, which they won with a landslide majority of 179.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The electorate was asked to vote on two sets of statements which corresponded to both proposals.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Scottish Labour, the SNP, Scottish Liberal Democrats, and Scottish Greens campaigned for a "Yes" vote for both proposals whilst the Scottish Conservatives opposed both proposals.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Labour MP Tam Dalyell opposed the creation of the Parliament, but accepted that it should have tax-varying powers if it were to be established.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The official Yes campaign, *Scotland Forward* (styled "Scotland FORward"), was headed by the businessman Nigel Smith and came out of the groups that had previously formed the Scottish Constitutional Convention, along with the Scottish National Party.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was supported by the Labour, SNP, Liberal Democrat and Green parties.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The official No campaign, *Think Twice*, was headed by Brian Monteith, a former employee of the Conservative MP Michael Forsyth.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Board members included Donald Findlay, rector of the University of St Andrews and vice-chairman of Rangers F.C., and senior Conservative peer Lord Fraser.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] However, it struggled to get much business support as they were wary of opposing a project that had such support from the new government which had a large majority.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Campaigning in the referendum was suspended between the death and funeral of Diana, Princess of Wales.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was speculated that the Scottish referendum could have been postponed, but this would have required a recall of the UK Parliament and an amendment to the Referendums Act.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The result was "Yes-Yes": the majority voted "I agree" in favour of both proposals.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Two council areas had an overall "Yes-No" result – Dumfries and Galloway and Orkney.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] More votes were cast for the first question than the second in all regions (except Fife), with substantially more spoilt ballots for the second question, perhaps due to voter confusion over the two papers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Votes in favour of tax-varying powers still commanded significant majority, when compared to establishing the Parliament per se.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] A majority voted 'I agree' in every local council, apart from in Dumfries & Galloway and Orkney.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] In response to the majority voting for "Yes" to both proposals, the UK Parliament passed the Scotland Act 1998.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] This established a Scottish Parliament for the first time since the adjournment of the pre-Union Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The devolved Parliament convened for the first time in May 1999, following its first election.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was a poll that the Conservative Party had to fight despite losing their "No" Campaign and having no Westminster seats in Scotland after losing the 1997 general election.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Scotland Act 1998 also created the Scottish Executive, later to become known as the Scottish Government.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Professor Tom Devine, academic at the University of Edinburgh, dubbed the referendum result "the most significant development in Scottish political history since the Union of 1707".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Prime Minister Tony Blair claimed that "the era of big centralised government is over".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The "Yes" campaign leaders Donald Dewar (Scottish Labour) and Alex Salmond (Scottish National Party) held different views over the devolution proposal.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] However, they put their political differences aside immediately after the vote in celebration.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Despite this, the SNP's calls for independence soon reignited with SNP leader Alex Salmond claiming that there would be an independent Scotland within his lifetime.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] The "No" campaign did not share this optimism and feared that this vote was a catalyst towards the break-up of the Union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/1997-scottish-devolution-referendum] Detail was also lacking in that the Scottish Constitutional Convention had failed to address issues such as the role of The Queen or aspects of tax-varying powers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A referendum on Scottish independence from the United Kingdom was held in Scotland on 18 September 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The referendum question was "Should Scotland be an independent country?", which voters answered with "Yes" or "No".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The turnout of 84.6% was the highest recorded for an election or referendum in the United Kingdom since the January 1910 general election, which was held before the introduction of universal suffrage.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 set out the arrangements for the referendum and was passed by the Scottish Parliament in November 2013, following an agreement between the devolved Scottish government and the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The independence proposal required a simple majority to pass.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] All European Union (EU) or Commonwealth citizens residing in Scotland age 16 or over could vote, with some exceptions, which produced a total electorate of almost 4,300,000 people.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This was the first time that the electoral franchise was extended to include 16- and 17-year-olds in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Yes Scotland was the main campaign group for independence, while Better Together was the main campaign group in favour of maintaining the union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Many other campaign groups, political parties, businesses, newspapers, and prominent individuals were also involved.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Prominent issues raised during the referendum included what currency an independent Scotland would use, public expenditure, EU membership, and North Sea oil.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] An exit poll revealed that retention of the pound sterling was the deciding factor for those who voted No, while "disaffection with Westminster politics" was the deciding factor for those who voted Yes.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Kingdom of Scotland and the Kingdom of England were established as independent countries during the Middle Ages.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] After fighting a series of wars during the 14th century, the two monarchies entered a personal union in 1603 (the Union of the Crowns) when James VI of Scotland also became James I of England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The two nations were temporarily united under one government when Oliver Cromwell was declared Lord Protector of a Commonwealth in 1653, but this was dissolved when the monarchy was restored in 1660.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Scotland and England united to form the Kingdom of Great Britain in 1707 (Wales had already been unilaterally incorporated into England in the mid-16th century).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scots favoured union to solve the economic problems caused by the failure of the Darien scheme and the English favoured it to secure the Hanoverian line of succession.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Great Britain in turn united with the Kingdom of Ireland in 1801, forming the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Most of Ireland left the Union in 1922 to form the Irish Free State; consequently, the full name of the United Kingdom since 1927 is the *United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland*.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Labour Party was committed to home rule for Scotland in the 1920s, but it slipped down its agenda in the following years.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish National Party (SNP) was founded in 1934, but did not achieve significant electoral success until the 1960s.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A petition calling for home rule, the Scottish Covenant, was signed by 2,000,000 people (out of a population of 5,000,000) in the late 1940s.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As James Callaghan's Labour Government of the late 1970s was pressured by the SNP, Scottish devolution was, for the first time, seriously proposed.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In a 1979 referendum for a devolved Scottish Assembly, a narrow majority of votes were cast in favour of devolution, but this had no effect due to a requirement that the number voting 'Yes' had to exceed 40% of the total electorate.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] No further constitutional reform was proposed until Labour returned to power in a landslide electoral victory in May 1997.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A second Scottish devolution referendum was held later that year, as promised in the Labour election manifesto.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Clear majorities expressed support for both a devolved Scottish Parliament (74.3% in favour) and that Parliament having the power to vary the basic rate of UK income tax (63.5% in favour).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scotland Act 1998 established the new Scottish Parliament, first elected on 6 May 1999, with power to legislate on unreserved matters within Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A commitment to hold an independence referendum in 2010 was part of the SNP's election manifesto when it contested the 2007 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The press were largely hostile towards the SNP, with a headline for *The Scottish Sun* in May 2007 stating – beside an image of a hangman's noose – "Vote SNP today and you put Scotland's head in the noose".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As a result of that election, the SNP became the largest party in the Scottish Parliament and formed a minority government led by the First Minister, Alex Salmond.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The SNP administration launched a 'National Conversation' as a consultation exercise in August 2007, part of which included a draft referendum bill, the *Referendum (Scotland) Bill*.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] After this, a white paper for the proposed Referendum Bill was published, on 30 November 2009.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It detailed four possible scenarios, with the text of the Bill and Referendum to be revealed later.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The scenarios were: no change; devolution per the Calman Review; further devolution; and full independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government published a draft version of the bill on 25 February 2010 for public consultation; *Scotland's Future: Draft Referendum (Scotland) Bill Consultation Paper* contained a consultation document and a draft version of the bill.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The consultation paper set out the proposed ballot papers, the mechanics of the proposed referendum, and how the proposed referendum was to be regulated.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The third proposal was for full independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the 3rd Scottish Parliament only 50 of 129 MSPs (47 SNP, 2 Greens, and Margo MacDonald) supported a referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government withdrew the bill in September 2010 after failing to secure opposition support.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The SNP repeated its commitment to hold an independence referendum when it published its manifesto for the 2011 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Days before the election, Salmond said that legislation for a referendum would be proposed in the "second half of the parliament", as he wanted to secure more powers for the Scottish Parliament via the Scotland Bill first.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the election, the SNP won 69 of the 129 seats, securing a majority in a proportional representative voting system.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] UK Prime Minister David Cameron congratulated Salmond on his 'emphatic win', but pledged to campaign for the Union if the SNP carried out their pledge to hold a referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In January 2012, the UK government offered to legislate to provide the Scottish Parliament with the powers to hold a referendum, providing it was 'fair, legal and decisive'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This would set 'terms of reference for the referendum', such as its question(s), elector eligibility, and which body would organise the vote.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As the UK government worked on legal details, including the timing of the vote, Salmond announced an intention to hold the referendum in the autumn of 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Negotiations continued between the two governments until October 2012, when the Edinburgh Agreement was reached.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Independence Referendum (Franchise) Act 2013 was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 27 June 2013 and received Royal Assent on 7 August 2013.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 26 November 2013, the Scottish government published *Scotland's Future*, a 670-page white paper laying out the case for independence and the means by which Scotland might become an independent country.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Government announced on 21 March 2013 that the referendum would be held on Thursday 18 September 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Some media reports mentioned that 2014 would be the 700th anniversary of the Battle of Bannockburn and that Scotland would also host the 2014 Commonwealth Games and the 2014 Ryder Cup.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Salmond agreed that the presence of these events made 2014 a "good year to hold a referendum".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Convicted prisoners were not able to vote in the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) had ruled that this restriction was unlawful, but Scottish judge Lord Glennie said that he believed the ECHR judgment would apply only to parliamentary elections.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Appeals against his ruling were rejected by the Court of Session in Edinburgh and the UK Supreme Court.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The normal voting age was reduced from 18 to 16 for the referendum, as it was a Scottish National Party policy to reduce the voting age for all elections in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The move was supported by Labour, the Liberal Democrats and the Scottish Greens.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In January 2012, Labour MSP Elaine Murray led a debate arguing that the franchise should be extended to Scots living outside Scotland, including the approximately 800,000 living in the other parts of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the House of Lords, Baroness Symons argued that the rest of the UK should be allowed to vote on Scottish independence because it would affect the whole country.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This argument was rejected by the UK government, as the Advocate General for Scotland Lord Wallace said that "whether or not Scotland should leave the United Kingdom is a matter for Scotland".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Wallace also pointed to the fact that only two of 11 referendums since 1973 had been across all of the United Kingdom.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Professor John Curtice cited the precedent of the 1973 Northern Ireland sovereignty referendum (the "border poll"), which allowed only those resident in a part of the UK to vote on its sovereignty.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] There was debate as to whether the Scottish Parliament had the power to legislate for a referendum relating to the issue of Scottish independence, as the constitution is a matter reserved to the UK Parliament.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government insisted in 2010 that they could legislate for a referendum, as it would be an "advisory referendum on extending the powers of the Scottish Parliament", whose result would "have no legal effect on the Union".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Lord Wallace, Advocate General for Scotland, said in January 2012 that holding a referendum concerning the constitution would be outside the legislative power of the Scottish Parliament and that private individuals could challenge a Scottish Parliament referendum bill.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The two governments signed the Edinburgh Agreement, which allowed for the temporary transfer of legal authority.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Per the Edinburgh Agreement, the UK government drafted an Order in Council granting the Scottish Parliament the necessary powers to hold, on or before 31 December 2014, an independence referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The draft Order was approved by resolutions of both Houses of Parliament, and the Order ("The Scotland Act 1998 (Modification of Schedule 5) Order 2013"), was approved by Queen Elizabeth II at a meeting of the Privy Council on 12 February 2013.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Under the powers temporarily transferred from Westminster under the section 30 Order, the Scottish Parliament adopted the Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Act was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 14 November 2013 and received Royal Assent on 17 December 2013.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Under section 36 of the Act, it came into force the day after Royal Assent.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission was responsible for overseeing the referendum, "with the exception of the conduct of the poll and announcement of the result, and the giving of grants.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In its role of regulating the campaign and campaign spending, the Electoral Commission will report to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] (...) The poll and count will be managed in the same way as [local] elections, by local returning officers (...) and directed by a Chief Counting Officer".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Edinburgh Agreement stated that the wording of the question would be decided by the Scottish Parliament and reviewed for intelligibility by the Electoral Commission.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government stated that its preferred question was "Do you agree that Scotland should be an independent country?" The Electoral Commission tested the proposed question along with three other possible versions.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Their research found that the "Do you agree" preface made it a leading question, which would be more likely to garner a positive response.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The question was amended to "Should Scotland be an independent country?", which the Electoral Commission found was the most neutral and concise of the versions tested.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the 2010 Draft Bill, the Scottish government proposed that there would be one designated campaign organisation for each outcome, both of which would be permitted to spend up to £750,000 on their campaign and to send one free mailshot to every household or voter in the referendum franchise.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] There was to be no public funding for campaigns.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Registered political parties were each to be allowed to spend £100,000.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This proposed limit on party spending was increased to £250,000 in 2012.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In 2013, new proposals by the Electoral Commission for the 16-week regulated period preceding the poll were accepted.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] They allowed the two designated campaign organisations to spend up to £1.5 million each and for the parties in Scotland to spend the following amounts: £1,344,000 (SNP); £834,000 (Labour); £396,000 (Conservatives); £201,000 (Liberal Democrats); £150,000 (Greens).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] An unlimited number of other organisations could register with the Electoral Commission, but their spending was limited to £150,000.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Groups spending more than £250,000 were required to submit audited returns to the Commission by 18 March 2015.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] According to the Scottish government's consultation paper published on 25 February 2010, the cost of the referendum was "likely to be around £9.5 million", mostly spent on running the poll and the count.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Costs would also include the posting of one neutral information leaflet about the referendum to every Scottish household, and one free mailshot to every household or voter in the poll for the designated campaign organisations.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In April 2013, the projected cost of the referendum was £13.3 million; the final administrative cost was £15.85 million.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign in favour of Scottish independence, Yes Scotland, was launched on 25 May 2012.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Its chief executive was Blair Jenkins, formerly the Director of Broadcasting at STV and Head of News and Current Affairs at both STV and BBC Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign was supported by the SNP, the Scottish Green Party (which also created "its own pro-independence campaign to run alongside Yes Scotland") and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] At its launch, Salmond stated that he hoped one million people in Scotland would sign a declaration of support for independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 22 August 2014, Yes Scotland announced that the one million target had been surpassed.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign in favour of Scotland remaining in the UK, Better Together, was launched on 25 June 2012.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It was led by Alistair Darling, former Chancellor of the Exchequer, and had support from the Conservative Party, Labour Party and Liberal Democrats.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Political advertising on television and radio in the UK was prohibited by the Communications Act 2003, with the exception of permitted party political broadcasts.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Three major cinema chains stopped showing adverts by referendum campaign groups after receiving negative feedback from their customers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In December 2013, the Better Together campaign declared that it had received donations of £2,800,000.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Six-figure contributions were made by businessmen Ian Taylor and Donald Houston, and by author C.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Almost 27,000 donations of under £7,500 had been received by the same date.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Rowling, who announced in June 2014 that she had given £1,000,000 to the Better Together campaign.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the following month, whisky distiller William Grant & Sons announced a donation of approximately £100,000.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 12 August 2014, Better Together announced that it had raised enough money to cover the maximum spending permitted and was no longer accepting donations.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This was attributed in part to a large number of small donations being received after the first televised debate between First Minister Alex Salmond and Labour MP Alistair Darling.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As of May 2014, the Yes Scotland campaign had declared £4,500,000 in cash donations.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] EuroMillions lottery-winners Chris and Colin Weir gave £3,500,000.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A six-figure donation was given by investment fund manager Angus Tulloch; approximately 18,000 donations of less than £7,500 had been made by the same date.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Voting for the referendum commenced on 27 August 2014, with the receipt of ballots by postal voters.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As of 15 August, 680,235 eligible voters had registered for postal voting, a 20% increase compared with March 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] During the postal vote phase, Police Scotland arrested a man from Glasgow on suspicion of selling his vote on eBay.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The registration deadline for referendum voters was 2 September 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Several councils reported the processing of "unprecedented" numbers of new registrations, while others received "tens of thousands" of applications in the final week.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The UK Government said that, if a simple majority of the vote was in favour of independence, then 'Scotland would become an independent country after a process of negotiations'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] If the majority opposed independence, Scotland would remain part of the United Kingdom.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Further powers would be devolved to the Scottish Parliament as a result of the Scotland Act 2012.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission prepared an information leaflet which confirmed that the UK and Scottish governments had reached agreement on these points.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Cameron said in May 2014 that he believed that the referendum would be 'irreversible and binding'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the week before the referendum, both sides said they would abide by the result.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Salmond said that it was a 'once in a generation' event, citing the precedent of the two devolution referendums in 1979 and 1997.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the event of a majority for Yes, the Scottish Government had proposed an independence date of 24 March 2016.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It was suggested that, after negotiations concluded, the UK Parliament would legislate for Scottish independence to take place on the date that had been negotiated.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A report by a UK House of Lords committee published in May 2014 said that the UK could opt to delay the independence date.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, as part of a European Union (EU) member state, Scottish farmers received £583 million in subsidy payments from the EU under the Common Agricultural Policy (CAP).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Annual CAP payments are made to the UK, which then determines how much to allocate to each of the devolved administrations, including Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In the last CAP agreement, farmers in the UK qualified for additional convergence payments because Scottish farmers received a lower average single farm payment per hectare, mainly due to the mountainous terrain in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Supporters of independence therefore believed that an independent Scotland would receive greater agricultural subsidies as an independent state.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Opponents of independence believed that Scottish farmers benefited from the Union because the UK was one of the larger EU member states, and therefore had a greater say in CAP negotiations.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] They also questioned whether an independent Scotland would immediately receive full subsidy payments from the EU, as recent new member states had their subsidies phased in.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At the time of the independence referendum, the UK had some opt-outs from EU policies.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] One was the opt-out from the Schengen Area, meaning there were full passport checks for travellers from other EU countries except the Republic of Ireland, which was part of a Common Travel Area (CTA) with the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government proposed that an independent Scotland would remain outside the Schengen Area and remain inside the CTA, ensuring that no passport controls would be needed at the Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Nicola Sturgeon commented that an independent Scotland would negotiate with the EU to have the same visa arrangements as the UK has.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Alistair Carmichael, the Secretary of State for Scotland, said in January 2014 that it would make sense for Scotland to be in the CTA, but it would have to operate similar immigration policies to the rest of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This position was supported by Home Secretary Theresa May, who said in March 2014 that passport checks should be introduced if Scotland adopted a looser immigration policy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Conservative MP Richard Bacon said there would be "no reason" for border controls to be implemented.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In the white paper *Scotland's Future*, the Scottish government pledged to expand childcare provision in an independent Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The paper stated that this policy would cost £700 million, but that this would be financed by increased tax revenue from an additional 100,000 women returning to work.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In March 2014, the National Day Nurseries Association said that the plan could not be implemented unless greater funding was provided by local authorities to private nurseries.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A report by the Scottish Parliament Information Centre questioned the economic benefit of the policy, pointing out that there were only 64,000 mothers of children aged between 1 and 5 who were economically inactive.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government proposed that all British citizens who had been born in Scotland would automatically become Scottish citizens on the date of independence, regardless of whether or not they were then living in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] British citizens "habitually resident" in Scotland would also be considered Scottish citizens, even if they already held the citizenship of another country.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Every person who would automatically be considered a Scottish citizen would be able to opt-out of Scottish citizenship provided they already held the citizenship of another country.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] UK Home Secretary Theresa May said the future policies of an independent Scottish government would affect whether Scottish citizens would be allowed to retain British citizenship.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] An analysis paper published by the UK government in January 2014 stated that it was likely that Scots would be able to hold dual citizenship; however, the duality was considered for all other countries, not specifically to the rest of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The possibility of holding dual UK–Scotland citizenships could be subject to the "proof of affinity".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A YouGov poll in early September showed 25 per cent of the electorate believed MI5 was working with the British government to block independence, with many voters so fearful that the marks made by the pencils provided in polling stations would be tampered with that they brought their own pens.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP said that there was a defence underspend of 'at least £7.4 billion' between 2002 and 2012 in Scotland and that independence would allow the Scottish government to correct this imbalance.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In its white paper, the Scottish government planned that an independent Scotland would have a total of 15,000 regular and 5,000 reserve personnel across land, air and maritime forces by 2026.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In July 2013, the SNP proposed that there would be a £2.5 billion annual military budget in an independent Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The House of Commons Defence Select Committee said that the £2.5bn budget was too low.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Andrew Murrison, UK Minister for International Security Strategy agreed and said it was 'risible' for the SNP to suggest it could create an independent force by 'salami-slicing' from current British armed forces units.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The House of Commons defence committee also stated that Scottish independence would have a negative effect on its industry, while the UK government said it would not be willing to build warships in a foreign country.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The chief executive of Thales, one of Britain's largest defence suppliers, said that if Scotland became independent that this might raise questions about continued investment from his firm.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Royal United Services Institute said in 2012 that an independent Scotland could set up a Scottish Defence Force, comparable in size and strength to those of other small European states like Denmark, Norway, and Ireland, at an annual cost of £1.8 billion.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Dorcha Lee, a former colonel in the Irish Army, said that Scotland could eschew forming an army based on inherited resources from the British Army and instead follow an Irish model of a limited self-defence force.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At the time of the referendum, the Trident nuclear missile system was based at Coulport weapons depot and naval base of Faslane in the Firth of Clyde area.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP objected to having nuclear weapons on Scottish territory, but British military leaders said that there was no alternative site for the missiles.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In April 2014, several British military leaders co-signed a letter stating that forcing Trident to leave Scottish waters would place the UK nuclear deterrent in jeopardy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] *Nowhere to Go*, a report by Scottish CND, concluded that the removal of Trident from Scotland would force unilateral nuclear disarmament by the United Kingdom, as the weapons would have no viable alternative base.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A report by the Royal United Services Institute said that relocating Trident would be 'very difficult, but not impossible' and estimated it would take about 10 years and create an additional cost of around £3 billion.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] According to a seminar hosted by the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, that the Royal Navy would have to consider a range of alternatives, including disarmament.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A 2013 Scotland Institute report suggested a future Scottish government could be convinced to lease the Faslane nuclear base to the rest of the UK, in order to maintain good diplomatic relations and expedite NATO entry negotiations.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] SNP policy had historically been that an independent Scotland should not seek to obtain membership in NATO, but this was dropped after a vote by party members in 2012.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] MSPs John Finnie and Jean Urquhart resigned from the SNP over this policy change.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Green Party and Scottish Socialist Party continued their opposition to NATO membership.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP position that Trident nuclear weapons should be removed from Scotland but that it should hold NATO membership was criticised by Willie Rennie, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, and Patrick Harvie, co-convenor of the Scottish Green Party.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, Malcolm Chalmers of the Royal United Services Institute said that 'pragmatists' in the SNP accepted that NATO membership would likely involve a long-term basing deal, enabling the UK to keep Trident on the Clyde.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This was disputed by Mariot Leslie, a former UK permanent representative to NATO, who said that NATO would not want to disrupt its arrangements by excluding Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A UK government paper on security said that Police Scotland would lose access to the UK intelligence apparatus, including MI5, SIS, and GCHQ, and that an independent Scottish state would need to build security infrastructure.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Theresa May commented that an independent Scotland would have access to less security capability, but would not necessarily face a reduced threat.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] May also indicated that the British government would block Scotland from joining the Five Eyes intelligence-sharing alliance until Scotland had built up its own spying and intelligence infrastructure and was able to offer the alliance a "unique contribution".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, Allan Burnett, former head of intelligence with Strathclyde Police and Scotland's counter-terrorism coordinator until 2010, said that 'an independent Scotland would face less of a threat, intelligence institutions will be readily created, and allies will remain allies'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Baroness Ramsay, a Labour peer and former case officer with MI6, said that the Scottish government's stance on intelligence was 'extremely naïve' and that it was "not going to be as simple as they think".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Nicola Sturgeon said that Scotland would create a security service like MI5 to work alongside police and tackle terrorism, cyber-attacks and serious organised crime, and that creating an external intelligence agency would remain an option.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government and pro-independence campaigners said there was a democratic deficit in Scotland because the UK was a unitary state without a codified constitution.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP also called the unelected House of Lords an 'affront to democracy'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The 'democratic deficit' label has sometimes been used to refer to the period between the 1979 and 1997 UK general elections, during which the Labour Party held a majority of Scottish seats but the Conservative Party governed the whole of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond said in September 2013 that instances such as this amounted to a lack of democracy, and that 'people who live and work in Scotland are the people most likely to make the right choices for Scotland'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Menzies Campbell wrote in April 2014 that any democratic deficit had been addressed by creating the devolved Scottish Parliament, and that 'Scotland and the Scottish have enjoyed influence beyond our size or reasonable expectation' within the British government and the wider political system.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Conservative MP Daniel Kawczynski said in 2009 that the UK's asymmetric devolution had created a democratic deficit for England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This was commonly known as the West Lothian question, which cited the anomaly whereby English MPs could not vote on affairs devolved to Scotland but Scottish MPs could vote on the equivalent subjects in England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Kawczynski also pointed out that the average number of voters in a parliamentary constituency was larger in England than in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During the campaign, each of the three main UK parties conducted reviews of the UK constitution, with each recommending that more powers should devolve to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On the morning before a televised debate between Alex Salmond and Alistair Darling, Better Together published a joint statement.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Co-signed by the three main UK party leaders (David Cameron, Ed Miliband and Nick Clegg), it committed to granting Scotland increased power over domestic taxes and parts of the social security system.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Boris Johnson, the Conservative mayor of London, said he opposed giving the Scottish Parliament greater fiscal powers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During the second televised debate, Salmond challenged Darling to specify which additional powers that could help create greater employment in Scotland would be granted if there was a 'no' vote.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During a visit to Scotland later that week, David Cameron promised more powers 'soon'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On 8 September, former Prime Minister Gordon Brown suggested a timetable for the additional powers to be implemented in the event of a 'no' vote.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He proposed that work on a new Scotland Act would begin immediately after the referendum, resulting in the publication of a white paper by the end of November 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Two days before the referendum, the three main UK party leaders publicly pledged to introduce 'extensive new powers' by the timetable suggested and that the Barnett formula of public funding would continue.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A principal issue in the referendum was the economy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Weir Group, one of the largest private companies based in Scotland, commissioned a study by Oxford Economics into the potential economic effects of Scottish independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It found that Weir would pay more corporation tax, despite the Scottish government's proposal to cut the rate of corporation tax, due to it no longer being able to offset losses in Scotland against profits in the rest of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It also stated that independence would result in additional costs and complexity in the operation of business pension schemes.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report found that 70% of all Scottish exports are sold to the rest of the UK, which it said would particularly affect the financial services sector.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Standard Life, one of the Scottish financial sector's largest businesses, said in February 2014 that it had started registering companies in England in case it had to relocate some of its operations there.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In February 2014, the *Financial Times* noted that Scotland's per capita GDP was bigger than that of France when a geographic share of oil and gas was taken into account, and still bigger than that of Italy when it was not.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] As of April 2014, Scotland had a similar rate of unemployment to the UK average (6.6%) and a lower fiscal deficit (including as a percentage of GDP).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Scotland performed better than the UK average in securing new Foreign Direct Investment in 2012–13 (measured by the number of projects), although not as well as Wales or Northern Ireland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] GDP growth during 2013 was lower in Scotland than in the rest of the UK, although this was partly due to an industrial dispute at the Grangemouth Refinery.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Deutsche Bank issued a report in the week before the referendum in which David Folkerts-Landau, the bank's chief economist, concluded: 'While it may sound simple and costless for a nation to exit a 300-year-old union, nothing could be further from the truth'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Folkerts-Landau said the economic prospects after a 'yes' vote were 'incomprehensible', and cited Winston Churchill's 1925 Gold Standard decision and the actions of America's Federal Reserve that triggered the Great Depression of the 1930s as mistakes of a similar magnitude.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Swiss financial services company UBS supported Deutsche Bank's position.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Supporters of independence said that Scotland had not realised its full economic potential because it was subject to the same economic policy as the rest of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, the Jimmy Reid Foundation published a report stating that UK economic policy had become 'overwhelmingly geared to helping London, meaning Scotland and other UK regions suffer from being denied the specific, local policies they need'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Later in January 2014, Colin Fox said that Scotland is 'penalised by an economic model biased towards the South East of England'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In November 2013, Chic Brodie said that Scotland was deprived of economic benefit in the 1980s after the Ministry of Defence blocked oil exploration off the West of Scotland, ostensibly to avoid interference with the UK's nuclear weapons arsenal.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The UK Treasury issued a report on 20 May 2013 which said that Scotland's banking systems would be too big to ensure depositor compensation in the event of a bank failure.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report indicated that Scottish banks would have assets worth 1,254% of GDP, which was more than Cyprus and Iceland before the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It suggested Scottish taxpayers would each have £65,000 of potential liabilities during a hypothetical bailout in Scotland, versus £30,000 as part of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Economists including Andrew Hughes Hallett, Professor of Economics at St Andrews University, rejected the idea that Scotland would have to underwrite these liabilities alone.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He observed that banks operating in more than one country can be given a joint bailout by multiple governments.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In this way, France, Belgium, and the Netherlands collectively bailed out Fortis Bank and the Dexia Bank.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The American Federal Reserve System lent more than $1 trillion to British banks, including $446 billion to the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS), because they had operations in the United States.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Robert Peston reported in March 2014 that RBS and Lloyds Banking Group might be forced to relocate their head offices from Edinburgh to London in case of Scottish independence, due to a European law brought in after the 1991 collapse of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Financial groups including RBS, Lloyds, Clydesdale Bank, TSB, and Tesco Bank later announced that they planned to move their registered headquarters from Scotland to England if Scotland voted for independence, although most indicated that they had no immediate intention to transfer any jobs.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Another major economic issue was the currency that an independent Scotland would use.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The principal options were to establish an independent Scottish currency, join the euro, or retain the pound sterling (a form of currency substitution).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Throughout the 1990s and early 2000s, the SNP's policy was that an independent Scotland should adopt the euro, though this was relegated to a long-term rather than short-term goal by the party's 2009 conference.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] There was disagreement over whether Scotland would be required to join the euro if it became an EU member state in its own right.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] All new members are required to commit to joining the single currency, but they must first be party to ERM II for two years.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government argued that this was a *de facto* opt-out from the euro, because EU member states are not obliged to join ERM II.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] For example, the people of Sweden rejected adopting the euro in a 2003 referendum and its government subsequently refused to enter ERM II.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP favoured continued use of sterling in an independent Scotland through a formal currency union with the UK, with the Bank of England setting its interest rates and monetary policy and acting as its central bank.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In June 2012, Alistair Darling said voters in the rest of the UK could choose not to be in a currency union with Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Former Prime Minister Sir John Major rejected the idea of a currency union, saying it would require the UK to underwrite Scottish debt.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Former Prime Minister Gordon Brown said the SNP proposal would create a 'colonial relationship' between Scotland and Westminster.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Welsh First Minister Carwyn Jones said in November 2013 that he would seek a veto on a currency union between Scotland and the rest of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Yes Scotland said that a currency union would benefit both Scotland and the rest of the UK, as Scotland's exports would boost the balance of payments, and consequently strengthen the exchange rate of sterling.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Meanwhile, UK economists and financial experts said the effect on the balance of payments and the exchange rate would be 'largely neutral'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Sterling fell by almost one cent against the US dollar in a day early in September 2014, due to an opinion poll showing a swing towards the Yes campaign.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The *Financial Times* reported a few days later that 'Asset managers, investors and pension savers are moving billions of pounds out of Scotland' because of fears that Scotland would leave the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The newspaper also reported that '"exit clauses" are being inserted into commercial property contracts in Scotland to allow buyers to scrap deals or renegotiate prices if voters opt for independence'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Scottish Labour leader Johann Lamont said that any additional transaction costs would fall largely on Scottish companies, costing businesses in Scotland 11 times more than those in England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Institute of Directors said that any new transaction costs would 'pale in comparison to the financial danger of entering an unstable currency union'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Banking experts said that being the 'junior partner' in a currency arrangement could amount to 'a loss of fiscal autonomy for Scotland' if policy constraints were imposed on the Scottish state.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Angus Armstrong of the National Institute of Economic and Social Research wrote that the implicit constraints on its economic policy would be more restrictive than the explicit ones it faced as part of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond said in February 2014 that an independent Scotland in a currency union would retain tax and spending powers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The UK Chancellor George Osborne, as well as equivalent post-holders in the two other main UK political parties, rejected the idea of a formal currency union with an independent Scotland in February 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Shadow Chancellor Ed Balls said the SNP's proposals for a currency union were 'economically incoherent' and that any currency option for an independent Scotland would be 'less advantageous than what we have across the UK today'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] After the three main UK political parties ruled out a formal currency union, the Adam Smith Institute said that the economies of Panama, Ecuador, and El Salvador 'demonstrate that the informal use of another country's currency can foster a healthy financial system and economy'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In September 2014, former European Commissioner Olli Rehn said that an independent Scotland would be unable to meet EU membership requirements if it shared sterling informally, as it would not have an independent central bank.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond disputed this, restating his belief that a sterling currency union would be formed and pledging to create the necessary financial institutions.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Socialist Party favoured an independent Scottish currency, pegged to sterling in the short term.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Green Party said that keeping sterling as 'a short term transitional arrangement' should not be ruled out, but also that the Scottish Government should 'keep an open mind about moving towards an independent currency'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In early 2013, the Jimmy Reid Foundation described retention of the pound as a good transitional arrangement, but recommended the eventual establishment of an independent Scottish currency to 'insulate' Scotland from the UK's 'economic instability'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Other proponents of an independent Scottish currency included Yes Scotland chairman Dennis Canavan and former SNP deputy leader Jim Sillars.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On 9 September 2014, Mark Carney, governor of the Bank of England, said that a currency union between an independent Scotland and the remainder of the UK would be 'incompatible with sovereignty'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He added that cross-border ties on tax, spending and banking rules are a prerequisite: 'You only have to look across the continent to look at what happens if you don't have those components in place ...
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At present under devolution, Scotland controls only 7% of our revenues.' Carney's comments received vocal support from Darling and the GMB trade union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Barnett formula, introduced in the late 1970s, had resulted in higher per-capita public spending in Scotland than England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] If an allocation of North Sea oil revenue based on geography was included, Scotland also produced more per capita tax revenue than the UK average in the years immediately preceding the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Institute for Fiscal Studies reported in November 2012 that a geographic share of North Sea oil would more than cover the higher public spending, but warned that oil prices are volatile and that they are drawn from a finite resource.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Government Expenditure and Revenue Scotland report for 2012/13 found that North Sea oil revenue had fallen by 41.5% and that Scotland's public spending deficit had increased from £4.6 billion to £8.6 billion.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2012, the Scottish Government's Finance Secretary John Swinney prepared a confidential cabinet briefing paper on the financial impact of Scottish independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report warned that an independent Scotland would face public spending cuts, lower pensions and welfare spending, and high levels of debt.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report warned that Scotland's public finances would be heavily dependent on volatile and declining oil revenues, and suggested that the affordability of the state pension in an independent Scotland would be at risk.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report further warned that the SNP's plans for an oil fund under independence would "require some downward revision in current spending." Swinney's cabinet paper was kept secret before being leaked to the press in 2013, a year after it was drafted.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Alistair Darling, the leader of the Better Together campaign opposed to Scottish independence, described the leaked report as a "hammer blow" to the SNP's economic credibility.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A Scottish Government spokesman insisted that the report's findings had been "overtaken by events".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In May 2014, the UK government published an analysis identifying a 'Union dividend' of £1,400 per year for each person in Scotland, mainly due to the higher level of public spending.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government disputed this analysis, saying that each Scot would be £1,000 better off per year under independence by 2030.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Three economic experts said that both estimates were possible, but they depended on unknown variables such as the division of UK government debt, future North Sea oil revenues, possible spending commitments of an independent Scotland and future productivity gains.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In its analysis, the UK government also estimated setup costs of £1.5 billion (1% of GDP) for establishing an independent state, or possibly £2.7 billion (180 public bodies costing £15 million each).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Patrick Dunleavy of the London School of Economics criticised the UK government's 'ludicrous' use of his research in arriving at the latter figure.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Treasury said that their main figure (£1.5 billion) was based on estimates by Robert Young of Western University.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Two of the main unionist parties in Scotland called on the SNP to publish their own estimate of the setup costs of an independent state, but the Scottish government said that an estimate was not possible as the final bill would depend on negotiations with the rest of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Dunleavy estimated immediate setup costs of £200 million in a report commissioned by *The Sunday Post*, with 'total transition costs' of between £600 million and £1,500 million in the first 10 years of independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The credit rating that an independent Scotland would merit also became a subject of debate.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The credit-rating agency Fitch said in 2012 that it could not give an opinion on what rating Scotland would have, because Scottish finances would largely depend on the result of negotiations between the UK and Scotland and specifically the division of UK assets and liabilities.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Research published by Moody's in May 2014 said that an independent Scotland would be given an A rating, comparable with Poland, the Czech Republic and Mexico.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] An A rating would have been two grades below its then rating for the UK, which Moody's said would be unaffected by Scottish independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The UK government controlled most energy issues, although control over planning laws had allowed the Scottish government to prevent the construction of new nuclear power stations in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence wanted to retain a single energy market for the whole of Great Britain after independence, to maintain price stability and support for suppliers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents said that independence would threaten that single energy market.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Euan Phimister, professor of economics at Aberdeen University, said that although independence would affect the relationship, it was likely that there would be continued English demand for electricity generated in Scotland due to the lack of spare capacity elsewhere.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The second largest supplier of energy in the UK, SSE plc, believed that a single market would be the most likely outcome under independence, although it would require negotiations that may have led to changes to the existing system.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour MP Caroline Flint said that independence would mean higher energy bills in Scotland, as its customers would have to pay more to support renewable energy in Scotland, which represented one-third of the UK total.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Euan Phimister said that bills were likely to increase across the whole of Great Britain because renewable schemes and new nuclear power stations in England were receiving higher subsidies than the power plants which were due for closure due to environmental regulations.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He also said that there was a distinction between existing and proposed renewable schemes in that the existing schemes had already been paid for, whereas any new construction required the promise of subsidy from the consumer.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Energy and Climate Change Secretary Ed Davey said Scottish generators would no longer be eligible for UK subsidies, which would increase energy bills for consumers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Approximately 90% of the United Kingdom's North Sea oil fields were located in Scottish territorial waters.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The tax revenue generated from an offshore site was not counted within the nation or region nearest to it, but was instead allocated to the UK Continental Shelf.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The revenue from North Sea oil was used to support current expenditure, and the UK did not create a sovereign oil fund (as in Norway).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP believed that a portion of the revenues should have been invested in a sovereign oil fund.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government, citing industry body Oil and Gas UK, estimated in *Scotland's Future* that there were 24 billion barrels of oil equivalent still to be extracted.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir Ian Wood, founder of oil services company Wood Group, said in August 2014 that he believed there were between 15 and 16.5 billion boe and that the impact from declining production would be felt by 2030.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2014, an investigation by industry recruitment website *Oil and Gas People* found that there were extensive oil reserves to the west of the Western Isles and Shetland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The report anticipated that the region would be developed within the next 10 years because of improvements in drilling technology, rig design and surveying.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP advocated that an independent Scotland should become a full member state of the European Union (EU) with some exemptions, such as not having to adopt the euro.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was debate over whether Scotland would be required to reapply for membership and whether it could retain the UK's opt-outs.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The European Commission (EC) offered to provide an opinion to an existing member state on the matter, but the UK government confirmed it would not seek this advice, as it did not want to negotiate the terms of independence in advance of the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was no precedent for an EU member state dividing into two sovereign countries after joining the EU.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence stated that an independent Scotland would become an EU member by treaty amendment under Article 48 of the EU treaties.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents said that this would not be possible and that an independent Scotland would need to apply for EU membership under Article 49, which would require ratification by each member state.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, Christina McKelvie, Convener of the European and External Relations Committee of the Scottish Parliament, asked Viviane Reding, Vice-President of the European Commission, whether Article 48 would apply.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Reding replied that EU treaties would no longer apply to a territory that secedes from a member state.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] She also said that Article 49 would be the route to apply to become a member of the EU.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] José Manuel Barroso, president of the European Commission, said earlier that an independent Scotland would have to apply for EU membership, while the rest of the UK would continue to be a member.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In 2014, he reiterated that for Scotland to join the EU would be 'extremely difficult, if not impossible'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former prime minister Sir John Major suggested in November 2013 that Scotland would need to reapply for EU membership, but that this would mean overcoming opposition to separatism among other member states.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Salmond cited a letter from Mario Tenreiro of the EC's secretariat general that said it would be legally possible to renegotiate the situation of the UK and Scotland within the EU by unanimous agreement of all member states.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Spain's European Affairs minister reiterated their position two days before the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir David Edward, a former European Court judge, said that the EU institutions and member states would be 'obliged' to start negotiations before independence took effect to decide the future relationship.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He said this would be achieved by agreed amendment of the existing Treaties (Article 48), rather than a new Accession Treaty (Article 49).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Graham Avery, the EC's honorary director-general, agreed with Edward.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Avery wrote a report, published by the European Policy Centre, which said that EU leaders would probably allow Scotland to be part of the EU because of the legal and practical difficulties that would arise from excluding it.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In a research paper, Professor Sionaidh Douglas-Scott of Oxford University wrote that the EU law normally takes a 'pragmatic and purposive approach' to issues not already provided for by existing treaties.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In January 2013, the Republic of Ireland's Minister of European Affairs, Lucinda Creighton, said that if Scotland were to become independent, it 'would have to apply for membership and that can be a lengthy process'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] She later clarified those remarks, writing that she 'certainly did not at any stage suggest that Scotland could, should or would be thrown out of the EU'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He also said that Barroso's comments on the legal position had 'no basis in the European treaties'.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In January 2013, David Cameron committed the Conservative Party to a referendum before the end of 2017 on UK membership of the EU if they won the 2015 general election.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Legislation for an in/out EU referendum was approved by the House of Commons in November 2013.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Studies showed some divergence in attitudes to the EU in Scotland and the rest of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In contrast, there was a majority for withdrawal in England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Yes Scotland said that the UK government plans for an EU referendum had caused "economic uncertainty" for Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During a CBI Scotland event attended by Cameron, businessman Michael Rake criticised him for creating uncertainty about EU membership.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In response to such criticism, Cameron pointed to examples of inward investment in the UK that he said was not happening in the rest of Europe.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some commentators suggested that the UK leaving the EU could undermine the case for Scottish independence, since free trade, freedom of movement and the absence of border controls between Scotland and England could no longer be assumed.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Responsibility for most aspects of health care was devolved to the Scottish Parliament when it was established in 1999.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government enacted health policies which were different from those in England, such as abolishing charges for prescriptions and elderly personal care.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] NHS Scotland was operationally independent of the NHS in the rest of the United Kingdom since the formation of the NHS in 1948.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence argued that independence was needed because possible reductions in the NHS budget in England would result in reduced funding for Scotland, which would make it difficult to maintain the existing service.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Harry Burns, a former chief medical officer for Scotland, said in July 2014 that he thought independence could be beneficial for public health because it may give people greater control of their lives.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In May 2014, about 100 medical workers, including surgeons, consultant doctors, GPs, pharmacists, dentists, hospital porters and janitors joined a pro-independence campaign group called "NHS for Yes".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In contrast, opponents argued that a subsequent drop in funding to an independent Scottish Government would have a significantly larger effect upon the budget.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Concerns were also raised about the impact on the medical research sector in Scotland from the loss of UK wide research funding.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Two days before the referendum, papers indicating "a funding gap of £400–£450m in the next two financial years, 2015–17", for Scotland's NHS, resulting from Scottish government policies, were leaked to the media.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A Scottish government spokesperson commented that the papers were from "part of the regular discussions among NHS leaders to plan for NHS Scotland's future".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents of independence said that being part of the UK was crucial in allowing Scots to obtain specialist treatment elsewhere in the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Although operationally independent, NHS Scotland had reciprocal arrangements in place with the NHS services in the rest of the UK and specialist services were shared.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Vote No Borders, a unionist campaign group, ran a cinema advert which claimed that Scots would find it more difficult to obtain treatment at the Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH), a London facility which provided specialist care for children.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Vote No Borders withdrew the advert after GOSH complained that it had not been consulted about the advert and stated that they had reciprocal health care agreements with numerous countries.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The white paper on independence proposed that an independent Scotland would open around 100 embassies around the world.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Prime Minister David Cameron suggested that an independent Scotland would be "marginalised" at the United Nations, where the UK is a permanent member of the Security Council.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former Prime Minister John Major suggested that the UK could lose its permanent seat at the Security Council if Scotland became independent.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Forming a republic was favoured by some pro-independence political parties and organisations, including the Scottish Green Party and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP favoured an independent Scotland continuing to recognise Elizabeth II as Queen of Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Christine Grahame MSP said she believed that party policy was to hold a referendum on the matter, due to a 1997 SNP conference resolution.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some media reports suggested that the announcement on 8 September of the pregnancy of the Duchess of Cambridge with her second child would help pro-union sentiment.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Queen's official position on Scottish independence was neutral.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Just prior to the referendum, Elizabeth II said in a private conversation that she hoped people would "think very carefully about the future".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UK State Pensions were managed by the UK government, paying £113.10 per week to a single person who is of state pension age in the 2013/14 tax year.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The state pension age for men was 65, but this was due to rise to 66 in 2020 and 67 by 2028.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Research by the National Institute of Economic and Social Research found that an independent Scotland could delay these increases, due to a lower life expectancy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The *Scotland's Future* white paper pledged to maintain a state pension at a similar rate to the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former UK Prime Minister Gordon Brown said in April 2014 that Scotland had an above-average share of the public-sector pension bill and concluded that pensions would be protected by sharing risks and resources within the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UK government pensions minister Steve Webb said in May 2014 that Scots would be entitled to the current levels of state pension after independence because they had accumulated rights within the existing system.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Webb went on to say that there would need to be negotiations between the UK and Scotland as to how these pensions would be paid.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In relation to private pension schemes, a report by the Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland expressed concern that there were no plans to deal with EU regulations that may affect the funding of cross-border defined benefit schemes.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The EC decided in March 2014 not to relax these regulations, which require cross-border schemes to be fully funded.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scotland hosted the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, less than two months before the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish team won a record number of gold medals, which the writer Alan Bisset said would help give voters more belief and confidence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *Sunday Herald* columnist Ian Bell took an opposing view, saying that sporting success would be unlikely to aid support for independence, due to the lengthy and passionate debate on the subject.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former Labour first minister Henry McLeish published a report in May 2014 that found no obvious barriers to an independent Scotland competing in the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] McLeish said that some athletes, particularly those in team sports, may choose to compete for the existing Great Britain team rather than Scotland, as they would be nationals of both states.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Gordon Brown pointed to the 2012 medal count for Great Britain, saying that it showed the success of the union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scottish athletes were involved in 13 of the 65 medals won by Great Britain in 2012, but only three of those were won without assistance by athletes from other parts of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir Chris Hoy said in May 2013 that it would "take time" for Scottish athletes to "establish themselves in a new training environment", and indicated that the good performance of Scottish athletes in the Great Britain team would not automatically translate into that of an independent Scotland team.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Hoy also said that he believed the lack of facilities and coaching infrastructure in Scotland would have to be addressed by an independent state.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The prospect of an independent Scotland raised questions about the future of the Northern Isles (Orkney and Shetland) and the Western Isles, island groups off the Scottish mainland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some islanders called for separate referendums to be held in the islands on 25 September 2014, one week after the Scottish referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, the Scottish Parliament published an online petition it had received calling for such referendums, which was supported by Shetland MSP Tavish Scott.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The proposed referendums would have asked islanders to choose from three options: that the island group should become an independent country; that it should remain in Scotland; or that (in the event of Scottish independence) it should remain in the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The third option would have implemented a conditional promise made in 2012 by an SNP spokesperson, who said that Orkney and Shetland could remain in the United Kingdom if their "drive for self-determination" was strong enough.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Politicians in the three island groups referred to the Scottish referendum as the most important event in their political history "since the inception of the island councils in 1975".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Angus Campbell, leader of the Western Isles, said that the ongoing constitutional debate offered the "opportunity for the three island councils to secure increased powers for our communities to take decisions which will benefit the economies and the lives of those who live in the islands".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In a meeting of the island councils in March 2013, leaders of the three territories discussed their future in the event of Scottish independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] This included whether the islands could demand and achieve autonomous status within either Scotland or the rest of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Among the scenarios proposed were achieving either Crown Dependency status or self-government modelled after the Faroe Islands, in association with either Scotland or the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Steven Heddle, Orkney's council leader, described pursuing Crown Dependency status as the least likely option, as it would threaten funding from the EU, which was essential for local farmers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alasdair Allan, MSP for the Western Isles, said independence could have a positive impact on the isles, as "crofters and farmers could expect a substantial uplift in agricultural and rural development funding via the Common Agricultural Policy if Scotland were an independent member state of the EU".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In July 2013, the Scottish government made the Lerwick Declaration, indicating an interest in devolving power to Scotland's islands.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] By November, it had committed to devolving further powers to Orkney, Shetland and the Western Isles in the event of independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Steven Heddle called for legislation to that effect to be introduced regardless of the referendum result.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He stated that he did not want such circumstances to arise, "and the best way to avoid this was to vote no in the referendum".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In 2012–13, Scottish universities received 13.1% of Research Councils UK funding.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alan Trench of University College London said that Scottish universities had received a "hugely disproportionate" level of funding and would no longer be able to access it following independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Willie Rennie, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, suggested that independence would mean Scottish universities losing £210m in research funding.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Institute of Physics in Scotland warned that access to international facilities such as the CERN Large Hadron Collider, the European Space Agency, and European Southern Observatory could require renegotiation by the Scottish government.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It also expressed concerns about research funding from UK charities and the reaction of international companies with Scottish facilities.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government's education secretary, Michael Russell, said that Scotland's universities had a "global reputation" that would continue to attract investment after independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2013, the principal of the University of Aberdeen said that Scottish universities could continue to access UK research funding through a "single research area" that crossed both nations' boundaries.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] David Bell, professor of economics at the University of Stirling, said that cross-border collaboration might continue, but Scottish universities could still lose their financial advantage.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Roger Cook of the Scotland Institute pointed out that although Scottish universities had received a higher share of Research Councils funding, they were much less dependent on this as a source of funding than their counterparts in England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professors from Scotland's five medical schools wrote an open letter warning that independence would mean Scotland's researcher base being "denied its present ability to win proportionately more grant funding".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Questions were asked whether Scotland, as an economy of a smaller size than the UK, would still support the same level of research activity, and what additional efforts might be required to establish a system of research councils "north of the border".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Jo Shaw, Salvesen chair of European institutions at the University of Edinburgh, noted that in smaller states, relationships between universities and research funders became "cosy", and led to a "corporatist" approach.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the time of the referendum, Students domiciled in Scotland did not pay tuition fees.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Students domiciled in the rest of the UK were charged fees of up to £9,000 per annum by Scottish universities, but those from other EU member states were not charged fees due to EU law.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] If Scotland had become an independent state, students from the rest of the UK would have been in the same position as students from the rest of the EU.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A University of Edinburgh study found that this would cause a loss in funding, which could have squeezed out Scottish students.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It concluded that the EU may allow a quota system for some specialist subjects, such as medicine, where there was a clear need for local students to be trained for particular careers, but that other subjects would not be eligible.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The study also found that their third suggestion would run against the spirit of the Bologna agreement, which aimed to encourage EU student mobility.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government stated in its white paper, *Scotland's Future*, that the present tuition fees arrangement would remain in place in an independent Scotland, as the EU allowed for different fee arrangements in "exceptional circumstances".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Ján Figeľ, a former EU commissioner for education, said in January 2014 that it would be illegal for an independent Scotland to apply a different treatment to students from the rest of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A report by a House of Commons select committee stated that it would cost an independent Scottish government £150 million to provide free tuition to students from the rest of the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A group of academics campaigning for independence expressed concern that the present arrangements would not continue if Scotland stayed within the UK, due to public spending cuts in England and the consequential effects of the Barnett formula.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Yes campaign argued that control of welfare policy would be a major benefit of independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] According to the Institute for Fiscal Studies, independence would "give the opportunity for more radical reform, so that the [welfare] system better reflects the views of the Scottish people".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Yes Scotland and deputy first minister Nicola Sturgeon said the existing welfare system could only be guaranteed by voting for independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2013, the Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations (SCVO), which represents charities, called for a separate welfare system to be established in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In November 2013, the Scottish government pledged to use the powers of independence to reverse key aspects of the Welfare Reform Act 2012, which was implemented across the UK despite opposition from a majority of Scotland's MPs.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It said it would abolish Universal Credit and the bedroom tax.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP also criticised Rachel Reeves, Labour's shadow secretary of state for work and pensions, for saying that a future UK Labour government would be even tougher on benefits than the Cameron–Clegg coalition government.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour politician Jim Murphy, a former Secretary of State for Scotland, said that he was "fiercely committed" to devolving welfare powers to the Scottish Parliament, but also warned that independence would be disruptive and would not be beneficial.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scottish Labour's Devolution Commission recommended in March 2014 that some aspects of the welfare state, including housing benefit and attendance allowance, should be devolved.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Feminist economist Ailsa McKay, a supporter of the Radical Independence movement, argued that an independent Scotland should change its welfare system dramatically by offering all its people a basic income.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A number of demonstrations in support of independence were co-ordinated following the announcement of the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The March and Rally for Scottish Independence in September 2012 drew a crowd of between 5,000 and 10,000 people to Princes Street Gardens.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The event was repeated in September 2013; police estimated that over 8,000 people took part in the march, while organisers and the Scottish Police Federation claimed between 20,000 and 30,000 people took part in the combined march and rally.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The March and Rally was criticised in both 2012 and 2013 for the involvement of groups like the Scottish Republican Socialist Movement and Vlaamse Volksbeweging.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Five days before the referendum vote, the Orange Order – a Protestant brotherhood – held a major anti-independence march and rally in Edinburgh.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It involved at least 15,000 Orangemen, loyalist bands and supporters from Scotland and across the UK, and was described as the biggest pro-Union demonstration of the campaign up to that date.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A rally for UK unity, organised by the Let's Stay Together campaign, was attended by 5,000 people in London's Trafalgar Square on the Monday preceding the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Similar events were held in London, Bristol, Leeds, Cardiff, Manchester and Belfast on the day before the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour MP Jim Murphy conducted a Scotland-wide tour to campaign for the No side, intending to visit 100 towns and cities in 100 days before the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 28 August he suspended his tour, after being hit by an egg in Kirkcaldy, and it was resumed on 3 September.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Murphy said that he had been subjected to "co-ordinated abuse" from Yes supporters and pointed to evidence of this on social media.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Better Together released footage of events in the tour where he was heckled by members of the public, some of whom called him a "traitor", "parasite", "terrorist" and "quisling".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] David Cameron said that "there's nothing wrong with a bit of heckling, but throwing things isn't necessarily part of the democratic process".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alex Salmond pointed out that people had "every entitlement to peaceful protest", but also said that "people shouldn't throw eggs at somebody full stop".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the launch of the Yes Scotland campaign in May 2012, Alex Salmond said that the case for independence would be driven by community activism and "online wizardry".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The not-for-profit and non-partisan *What Scotland Thinks* project tracked poll and survey data, including online activity, during the referendum campaign.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Using data from the Applied Quantitative Methods Network (AQMeN) research centre, the project compiled the social media activity of the two main campaigns, Yes Scotland and Better Together, by monitoring their respective Facebook and Twitter accounts since August 2013.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *What Scotland Thinks* published a report in February 2014 stating that the Yes Scotland campaign was gaining more Facebook likes.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Following the launch of the White Paper on 26 November, the average gap between the two Facebook pages grew from about 8,000 to about 23,000 by February 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Analysis of the campaigns' Twitter accounts showed the gap between the campaigns increased from approximately 8,000 followers in August 2013 to 13,804 followers in February 2014, in favour of Yes Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The project published a further report in June 2014 saying that greater online activity for Yes Scotland had continued.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professor Michael Keating said in April 2014 that the pro-independence movement was visibly stronger and fighting a "ground war", while unionist supporters were fighting an "'air war' of facts and figures".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The launch of online celebrity videos from both viewpoints was reported by the media in mid-July 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The "Let's Stay Together" campaign group produced a YouTube video called "'Scotland, you're my best friend'", featuring John Barrowman, Ross Kemp and Eddie Izzard.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A pro-independence video was produced by Yes Scotland and appeared on the campaign's YouTube channel.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Titled "✘ on September 18th #voteYes", the video features 32 people, including David Hayman, Martin Compston and Stuart Braithwaite.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The pro-independence organisation National Collective was identified by the *Independent* newspaper as the initiators of an online hashtag campaign that began in mid-August 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Writing for the *Independent*, Antonia Molloy said that the previous "#IndyReasons" hashtag campaign served as the inspiration for the "#YesBecause" campaign that was observed on the Twitter, Facebook and Vine social media platforms.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] From 21 August, users were invited to explain their reasons for voting "Yes" and #YesBecause was trending on Twitter after an hour from the launch.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) reported on 22 August that a "#NoBecause" campaign emerged in opposition to the Collective.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Debates over the issue of independence took place on television, in communities, and within universities and societies since the announcement of the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The STV current affairs programme *Scotland Tonight* televised a series of debates: Nicola Sturgeon v Michael Moore, Sturgeon v Anas Sarwar, Sturgeon v Alistair Carmichael and Sturgeon v Johann Lamont.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 21 January 2014, BBC Two Scotland broadcast the first in a series of round-table debates, which was filmed in Greenock and chaired by James Cook.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Yes campaign repeatedly called for a televised debate between UK Prime Minister David Cameron and First Minister of Scotland Alex Salmond.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] These calls for a one-on-one debate were dismissed by Cameron on the basis that the referendum is "for Scots to decide" and the debate should be "between people in Scotland who want to stay, and people in Scotland who want to go".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Calls for such a debate were also supported by former Prime Minister Gordon Brown who said it would be a "good idea".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Better Together chairman Alistair Darling accused Salmond of "running scared" from debating him instead, although Sturgeon stated in 2013 that a Salmond–Darling debate would take place at some point.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Darling refused a public debate with Yes Scotland chairman Blair Jenkins.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UKIP leader Nigel Farage also challenged Salmond to debate, but Farage was dismissed by an SNP spokeswoman as "an irrelevance in Scotland".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] After weeks of negotiation, a debate between Salmond and Darling was arranged.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The programme, titled as *Salmond & Darling: The Debate*, was broadcast by STV on 5 August 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The debate, moderated by Bernard Ponsonby, saw both politicians make opening statements and cross-examine each other before taking questions from the audience.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the end of the clash, they were both given the chance to make a closing speech.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Both campaign groups claimed victory in the debate.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A snap poll conducted by ICM stated Darling won the debate by 56% to 44%.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In his analysis of the ICM poll, Professor John Curtice detected little movement either way as a result of the debate.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A second debate between Salmond and Darling, titled *Scotland Decides: Salmond versus Darling* was shown on BBC One Scotland (and BBC Two in the rest of the UK) on 25 August, and was hosted by Glenn Campbell.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Salmond was perceived to have won the debate, and a snap poll conducted by ICM Research stated Salmond won the debate by 71% to 29%.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, BBC Scotland chiefs appeared before a Scottish Parliament committee to face questions from MSPs about the broadcaster's coverage.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During that session, BBC Scotland director Ken MacQuarrie disputed the findings of Robertson's study, saying that its conclusions were largely based upon "flawed analysis" and had contained factual errors.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During the latter stages of the campaign there were further allegations by some independence supporters that the BBC – the UK's national broadcaster – was biased against Scottish independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In an interview for the *Sunday Herald*, Alex Salmond said he believed the BBC had been unconsciously biased against independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former BBC journalist Paul Mason commented: "Not since Iraq have I seen BBC News working at propaganda strength like this".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The BBC replied that "Our coverage of the referendum story is fair and impartial in line with the editorial guidelines".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alex Massie wrote in *The Spectator* that the BBC's coverage was consistent with their attitude towards other government proposals of such magnitude and that it was incumbent upon the Yes campaign to prove its assertions.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 29 June, several hundred independence supporters gathered in a demonstration outside BBC Pacific Quay, the main BBC studio in Glasgow, in protest at its alleged bias.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A week before the vote, BBC political editor Nick Robinson said in a news item that Salmond "didn't answer" his questions at a press conference.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Several thousand independence supporters then protested at the BBC Scotland headquarters, accusing the BBC of broadcasting pro-Union "propaganda" and "lies".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *The Independent* reported that the protesters accused Robinson of working "with the Treasury to spread lies about the dangers to business and financial services of an independent Scotland".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alastair Campbell said that the "organised protests" amounted to media censorship "not far off" Vladimir Putin's Russia, telling Twitter users they should "Vote YES for intimidation".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The National Union of Journalists (NUJ) asked people to think about the implications of alleging journalistic bias when its members were only asking difficult questions.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Robinson later expressed his "regret" at using the phrase "didn't answer" in his report and criticised the protests.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Speaking after the referendum, Yes Scotland chief executive Blair Jenkins said that he did not believe there was a "systemic bias" against Yes or any "corporate intent to disadvantage the Yes campaign".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In addition to the incidents described above, there were reports of intimidation during the campaign.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A survey of the 133 business leaders who signed a public letter backing the Union reported that half of respondents "said that they had felt intimidated or pressurised by SNP or the Yes campaign as a result of their views".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The *Daily Telegraph* reported that other businesspeople had been unwilling to express an opinion on the referendum publicly because they were concerned about a loss of business from the SNP-led Scottish government or local government.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The NUJ called for abuse and bullying of its members, which had been led by online attacks, to end, commenting that, "For the duration of the referendum there has been hostility to journalists doing their jobs".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish Police Federation stated that criminal acts related to the referendum were few in number and criticised those "suggesting a minority of mindless idiots are representative of anything".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professor John Curtice stated in January 2012 that polling showed support for independence at 32%–38% of the Scottish population, which represented a slight decline from 2007, when the SNP had first formed the Scottish government.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] By 2012, there had been no poll evidence of majority support for independence, although the share "vehemently opposed to independence" had declined.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] According to Curtice, the polls were stable during most of 2013, with "no" leading by an average of 17% with a year to go.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Polling expert Nate Silver said in 2013 that the yes campaign had "virtually no chance" of winning the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] After the referendum, Silver said that although his prediction had been proven "right" he had done little research beforehand.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The gap narrowed after the release of the Scottish government white paper on independence: an average of five polls in December 2013 and January 2014 gave 39% yes and 61% no, once 'don't knows' had been excluded.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The polls tightened further after the Chancellor of the Exchequer, George Osborne, stated in February that the UK government was opposed to a currency union; the average yes support increased to 43%, once 'don't knows' had been excluded.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was little movement in the following months, with the average continuing to show 43% yes and 57% no (excluding don't knows) in July 2014 and August 2014.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In early September, polls indicated that the vote would be closer than had been indicated earlier.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 6 September a YouGov poll gave those in favour 47% versus 45% for those against; excluding those undecided, the figures were 51% and 49%, respectively.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The final polls, taken in the last few days of the campaign, indicated a lead for No of between 4% and 6%.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Soon after polling stations had closed, YouGov released a final poll that had been taken during the day of voting, indicating 46% Yes, 54% No.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Writing after the referendum, Nate Silver pointed out that the final margin of victory for No was greater than that indicated by the opinion polls.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He suggested that this could have been due to less enthusiastic voters being more pro-Union, which may not have been reflected in the polls.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Stephen Fisher, a sociology professor at Oxford University, noted in a study of other constitutional referendums that pollsters had tended to overestimate the "Yes" option.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2015, a poll carried out by YouGov found a slight majority of support for independence among people born in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish Independence Referendum Bill identified the convener of the Electoral Management Board for Scotland as chief counting officer for the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The chief counting officer, Mary Pitcaithly, was supported by a counting officer in each of the 32 local authority areas of Scotland, who was typically the chief executive for that local authority.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Voting took place between 07:00 and 22:00 BST in "polling places", which included schools, church halls, libraries and community centres.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Those who were still queuing when polls closed were not denied the chance to vote.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Votes from the 32 local government areas were counted and announced by each area separately.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Results came in during the early hours of 19 September, with the first result being from Clackmannanshire, and the last being from Highland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] 55.3% voted against independence, with a turnout of 84.6%.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] 28 of the 32 council areas voted "No", although the four areas that voted "Yes" (Dundee, Glasgow, North Lanarkshire and West Dunbartonshire) contained over 20% of the Scottish electorate.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The overall turnout of 84.6% was very high for Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Turnout was around 50–60% for elections to the Scottish and UK parliaments in the early 21st century.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The most recent United Kingdom general election with a comparable turnout was in 1950, when 83.9% voted.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The last ballot in the United Kingdom with a higher turnout than 84.6% was in January 1910, when no women and fewer men were allowed to vote (i.e., before universal suffrage applied to UK elections).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Of the 32 areas, East Dunbartonshire had the highest turnout at 91.0%, and Glasgow the lowest at 75.0%.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An academic study, surveying 5,000 Scottish voters soon after the referendum, found that the majority for No was formed by an "unusual alliance" of the very young, average earners, Protestants and women.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The study supported polling evidence that there was a gender gap, but countered beliefs that higher earners had supported No and that younger voters had mostly voted Yes.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] According to John Curtice, polling evidence indicates that support for independence was highest among those aged in their late 20s and early 30s, with a higher No vote among those aged between 16 and 24.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] There was an age gap at the referendum, with elderly voters being the most likely to vote against independence and younger voters aged under 55, except for those aged between 16 and 24, generally being more in favour of independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This was picked up by other academics, with data from the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation study from 2012 indicating that the six most deprived local authorities in Scotland returned the highest Yes vote shares at the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This is an incomplete list as not all local authorities counted by ward or constituency.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The constituency results are primarily obtained through local authority breakdowns of the result or the constituency boundaries being co-terminous with the local government district.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the day of the referendum, Michael Ashcroft conducted a poll of over 2,000 voters to identify the major reasons for their voting choices.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This poll found that among No voters, more than half (57%) stated the pound sterling was one of the most important factors in their decision.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Among Yes voters, the biggest single motivation was "disaffection with Westminster politics".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Cameron admitted he was "very embarrassed" for revealing the Queen's political view, which she had guarded in her own comments.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Alex Salmond, the Scottish First Minister and leader of the SNP, stated that he accepted the "verdict of the people" and called upon "all Scots to follow suit in accepting the democratic verdict of the people of Scotland".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] He called the referendum a "triumph for the democratic process and for participation in politics".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] He also resigned as SNP leader and as First Minister, saying that "for me as leader my time is nearly over but for Scotland the campaign continues and the dream shall never die".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Northern Ireland's First Minister Peter Robinson and Welsh First Minister Carwyn Jones responded positively to the result.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Robinson was "delighted Scotland has voted to remain in the Union".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] There was a large international reaction to the results of the Scottish independence referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The White House congratulated Scotland on their "full and energetic exercise of democracy".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] President Barack Obama noted the "debate, discussion, and passionate yet peaceful deliberations" and welcomed the result, saying he looked forward to "continuing our strong and special relationship with all the people of Great Britain and Northern Ireland".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] John Baird, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Canada, welcomed the decision and praised the conduct of the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Angela Merkel, the Chancellor of Germany, said that, "We [the German government] have always respected the fact that this referendum was called and that the central government in London agreed to this.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] And now we respect the outcome of it as well".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] When asked how she felt about the result she replied "I will not comment on this but just smile".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] We look forward to working with all parties across these islands in the years ahead.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Good Friday Agreement of 1998 is the historic template for harmonious and mutually beneficial development of the totality of relationships among the peoples of these islands.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In particular, it has led to a transformation in relationships between the two great traditions on this island".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] We have noted that the UK government has extended concrete promises in this regard.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Facing the result of the referendum, Erna Solberg, Prime Minister of Norway, stated to Norwegian broadcaster NRK she was 'glad' Scotland chose to remain in the union and that Scottish independence could have become challenging for Norway as a neighboring country.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Spanish Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy, in a video message, said that the Scottish have avoided serious consequences and "have chosen the most favorable option for everyone; for themselves, for all of Britain, and for the rest of Europe".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Iñigo Urkullu, the President of the Basque Country, stated on the day of the referendum that as the British Government had allowed Scotland to freely decide its own future, the responsibility of the Basque government was to "follow Scotland's footsteps" in securing a similar agreement in Spain.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Artur Mas, President of the Generalitat of Catalonia, described the referendum as a model for a future vote in the Catalonia, and said "What happened in Scotland is not a setback for us, because what we really want in Catalonia is to have the chance to vote".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the day after the Scottish referendum, the Catalan parliament voted to hold a "popular consultation" on Catalan independence.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Spanish government said that such a vote would be unconstitutional, but a referendum was held on 9 November 2014 anyway.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The large majority (80%) voted for Catalonia to be an independent country, although two-thirds of Catalans did not participate in the referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Secretary General of NATO Anders Fogh Rasmussen said that he fully-respected "the choice that the people of Scotland have made".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] President of the European Commission José Manuel Barroso said the Scottish vote was good for a "united, open, and stronger Europe".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Ten voters discovered that someone had voted under their names at polling stations in Glasgow, a method of fraud termed 'personation', and this led to an investigation by Police Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] During a BBC results broadcast, Scottish Conservative Party leader Ruth Davidson said that "No" campaigners had been "taking tallies" of postal votes and that those showed that the "No" campaign was in the lead.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This resulted in complaints to the electoral commission because the Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 stated that people attending proceedings related to the receipt of postal votes must not attempt to ascertain the outcome or "communicate any information" from that voting.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Electoral Commission, who could not investigate criminal allegations, passed the complaints onto Police Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A formal investigation was subsequently opened, which concluded that there was no criminality.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] According to official Russian observers, the conditions under which the votes were counted were not up to international standards and that the procedure used made it impossible to check on irregularities.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Russia's criticism came just months after the international community had rejected the results of a Kremlin-backed referendum held in the Russian-occupied Ukrainian territory of Crimea.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Russian officials said that the strong performance of the Scottish National Party (SNP) at the 2015 general election confirmed their suspicions about the Scottish independence referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A petition demanding a second referendum, based on allegations of vote-miscounting, gained more than 70,000 signatures within 24 hours.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In response, Chief Counting Officer Mary Pitcaithly declared that the referendum had been "properly conducted".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An official spokesperson reiterated this point, saying that they were "satisfied that all counts throughout Scotland were properly conducted" and that incidents in the footage could be "easily explained" and were being presented as a "'conspiracy' theory".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the night of 19 September, hundreds of unionists arrived to celebrate the 'No'-vote and some attacked independence supporters who had gathered in George Square, Glasgow.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Many of the unionists waved Union Jacks or loyalist flags and chanted "Rule, Britannia!" Police officers were drafted in to separate the groups but some unionists broke through police lines.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A number of people were reportedly beaten and bottles were thrown.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A press-photographer told *The Scotsman* he saw people being "kicked about" and was forced to flee after being threatened.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] By the end of the following month, the police had made 32 arrests in relation to the events.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The violence was condemned by politicians from both the 'Yes'- and 'No'-camps.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the weeks following the referendum, thousands of people joined the Scottish National Party, the Scottish Greens, or the Scottish Socialist Party, which had all campaigned for a 'Yes'-vote.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The parties claimed that many of the new members were former Scottish Labour Party members.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] By 2 October 2014, SNP membership had tripled from 25,000 to 75,000 people, overtaking the Liberal Democrats as the third-largest political party in the UK.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Conservative MP David Mundell said that 80,000 people had signed up to their "Friends of the Union" group during the campaign.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] These people had not necessarily become full members of the Conservative Party because they were not focussed on increasing the number of "card-carrying" members.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Following the referendum, there were calls for greater unity within Scottish unionism and to vote tactically against nationalist candidates.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A grassroots campaign called "Scotland in Union" aimed to encourage tactical voting at the 2015 general election and to publicise the benefits of Scotland being a part of the United Kingdom.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Analysis by the Electoral Reform Society prior to the 2015 general election identified some constituencies where tactical voting could succeed, but also pointed out that many voters would find it difficult to support another political party.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Writing after the election, Professor John Curtice said that in only one constituency (Edinburgh South) could it be said that tactical voting succeeded in defeating an SNP candidate.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Two days before the referendum, the leaders of the three main UK political parties publicly pledged to devolve "extensive new powers" to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] They also agreed to a timetable proposed by Gordon Brown.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In his speech responding to the referendum results, David Cameron said that an all-party commission, chaired by Lord Smith of Kelvin, would oversee the implementation of the new powers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Cameron also called for an answer to the West Lothian question, by removing the right of Scottish MPs to vote on legislation relating only to England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This proposal was opposed by Gordon Brown, who signed a petition calling for the additional powers to be devolved without any other conditions being attached.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The proposals were debated at length by the UK and Scottish parliaments.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The bill devolving further powers to Scotland was approved unanimously by the Scottish Parliament in March 2016.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Following the referendum, the SNP took a clear lead over the other parties in Scottish opinion polls.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the 2015 general election, the SNP received 1,454,436 votes, 49.97% of the Scottish vote and 56 out of the 59 Scottish seats contested in the election.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Labour lost forty of their forty-one seats and the Liberal Democrats lost ten of their eleven seats – all to the SNP.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The SNP replaced the Liberal Democrats as the third largest party in the House of Commons.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] As the Conservatives won an overall majority in the 2015 UK general election, a UK-wide referendum on European Union membership was held in June 2016.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An overall majority of the UK voted to leave the EU (for "Brexit"), while all of Scotland's council areas voted to remain in the EU.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Shortly afterwards, First Minister Nicola Sturgeon announced her intention to prepare legislation for a second independence referendum.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the June 2017 general election, the first major electoral test after the EU referendum, the SNP won 35 of the 59 Scottish seats in the House of Commons.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This represented a drop of 21 seats from 2015, with the Conservatives, Labour and Liberal Democrats all making gains.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Those results were largely reversed in the December 2019 general election, as the SNP won 48 seats and the Conservatives and Labour both made net losses.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] Written from a far left perspective, the book briefly covers Scottish ancient history, before documenting events from the Middle Ages until 2014, focussing on the struggle of workers and Scottish perspectives on the UK's political parties and sense of national identity.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] It was written by Trotskyist Chris Bambery.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] The book has fifteen chapters before its conclusion.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] It briefly mentions ancient history before delving into the Middle Ages, documenting the historical urbanisation of Scotland and the role of Scots in British colonisation campaigns.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] It notes the pattern of a few Scottish urbanites profiting from colonial conquests and sending their earnings to England, rather than benefiting the Scottish people.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] It notes the rising worker solidarity, from 1880s onwards, comparing the most robust rise of class consciousness with Wales, both more widespread than in England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] The book notes the Labour Party leader Ramsay MacDonald's support for austerity measures, costing the party support in Scotland in the 1930s.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] Bambery writes about the influence of folk music on the Scottish sense of national identity and as a tool to advance pacifism.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] He also notes the Scottish discomfort with the Communist Party of Britain and the influence of Thatcherite politics, prompting the 1997 Scottish devolution referendum, devolution, and the creation of the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] The book notes Scottish "disgust" for the Iraq War amidst wider protests against Tony Blair's "neoliberalism".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] Bambery describes Scottish National Party opportunism as deceptive, painting the party's politicians as being closer to neoliberalism than they claim.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] He describes Scottish independence voters as seekers of democracy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] The book's conclusion covers the increasing wealth gap in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] Paul Buhle, writing in *Monthly Review*, described the book as "splendid".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] Seán Damer, of Edinburgh University's School of Social and Political Science, described it as "well-written, well-documented, readable and provocative", crediting the author for telling history from the perspective of working-class Scots.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] He describes the book as being written from a Marxist perspective.*The Herald* gave the book a mixed review describing it as good and readable, but also characterising it as campaigning ahead of the 2014 independence referendum scheduled a few months after the book's publication.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The **Office of the Advocate General for Scotland** is a ministerial department of the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The position is currently occupied by Catherine Smith, Baroness Smith of Cluny.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office of Advocate General for Scotland was created in 1999 by the Scotland Act 1998 to be the chief legal adviser to the United Kingdom Government on Scots law.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] This function had previously been carried out by the Lord Advocate and Solicitor General for Scotland, who were transferred to the Scottish Government on the establishment of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office of the Advocate General for Scotland should not be confused with that of "His Majesty's Advocate", which is the term used for the Lord Advocate in Scottish criminal proceedings.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The first holder of the office was Lynda Clark, then Member of Parliament for Edinburgh Pentlands and from 2005 a member of the House of Lords as Baroness Clark of Calton.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 18 January 2006, Baroness Clark resigned to take up office as a Senator of the College of Justice, a judge of the Supreme Courts of Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office was then vacant until 15 March of that year when, under section 87 of the Scotland Act 1998, its functions were temporarily conferred on the Secretary of State for Scotland, Alistair Darling MP, himself a Scottish advocate.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] There had been substantial criticism from the judiciary and others of the length of time the office had been left vacant.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 21 March, however, it was announced Neil Davidson, former Solicitor General for Scotland, had been appointed Advocate General.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He was created a life peer, as Baron Davidson of Glen Clova, on 22 March 2006.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 14 May 2010, Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness, a former Deputy First Minister of Scotland, was appointed by the coalition government.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Richard Keen was appointed Advocate General in David Cameron's majority government on 29 May 2015, and has retained the post through two subsequent prime ministers to 2020.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He was created a life peer, as Baron Keen of Elie, on 8 June 2015.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He resigned on 16 September 2020 citing concerns arising from the UK Internal Market Bill, noting in his letter of resignation to Boris Johnson that he found it "increasingly difficult to reconcile what I consider to be my obligations as a Law Officer with your policy intentions".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Keith Stewart was appointed to succeed Keen on 15 October 2020.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Catherine Smith was appointed to the office and a life peerage by the Starmer government on 29 August 2024.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] All staff are on secondment or loan from other government organisations, mainly the Scottish Government and the Ministry of Justice.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights and made land more productive.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open-field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for oats.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] New monastic orders such as the Cistercians became major landholders and sheep farmers, particularly in the Borders where they were organised in granges.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late Medieval period, most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, known as husbandmen.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised for meat.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The rural economy appears to have boomed in the thirteenth century and in the immediate aftermath of the Black Death was still buoyant, but by the 1360s there was a severe falling off in incomes to be followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is roughly half the size of England and Wales and has approximately the same amount of coastline, but only between a fifth and a sixth of the amount of the arable or good pastoral land, under 60 metres above sea level, and most of this is located in the south and east.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This made marginal pastoral farming and fishing, the key factors in the pre-modern economy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Its east Atlantic position means that it has moderate rainfall: today about 700 mm per year in the east and over 1,000 mm in the west.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This encouraged the spread of blanket peat bog, the acidity of which, combined with high level of wind and salt spray, made most of the western islands treeless.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The existence of hills, mountains, quicksands and marshes made agriculture and internal communication difficult.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early Middle Ages, from the fifth century to the tenth century, were a period of climate deterioration, with a drop in temperature and an increase in rainfall, resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of significant transport links and wider markets, most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than wheat.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The evidence of bones indicates that cattle were by far the most important domesticated animal, followed by pigs, sheep and goats, while domesticated fowl were very rare.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Christian missionaries from Ireland may have changed agricultural practice, bringing innovations such as the horizontal watermill and mould board ploughs, which were more effective in turning the soil.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters of the Medieval Warm Period allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas in the south and east than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The feudalism introduced under David I, particularly in the east and south where the crown's authority was greatest, saw the placement of baronial lordships.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Land was now held from the king, or a superior lord, in exchange for loyalty and forms of service that were usually military.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Barons, who held feudal tenures, had the right to hold baronial courts, which could deal with matters of land ownership.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the imposition of feudalism continued to sit beside the existing systems of landholding and tenure and it is not clear how this change impacted on the lives of the ordinary free and unfree workers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In places, feudalism may have tied workers more closely to the land.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the predominantly pastoral nature of Scottish agriculture may have made the imposition of a manorial system, based on the English model, impracticable in some areas.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Obligations appear to have been limited to occasional labour service, seasonal renders of food, hospitality and money rents.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually included supplying oxen for ploughing the lord's land on an annual basis and the much resented obligation to grind corn at the lord's mill.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones, creating large tracts of land reserved for the leisure of the aristocracy and nobility.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were less rigorously enforced than in England, where the taking of wood and game were strictly forbidden, and all royal forests were on land already in the king's hands.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of new monastic orders such as the Cistercians in this period also brought innovations in agriculture.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Particularly in the Borders, their monasteries became major landholders, sheep farmers and producers of wool for the markets in Flanders.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were organised in granges, monastic farms run by lay brothers of the order.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Granges were theoretically within 30 miles of the mother monastery, so that those working there could return for services on Sundays and feast days.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were used for variety of purposes, including pastoral, arable and industrial production.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, to manage more distant assets in Ayrshire, Melrose Abbey used Mauchline as a "super grange", to oversee lesser granges.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some abbeys like Melrose had at least 12,000 sheep in the late thirteenth century.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This expanded from the use of small enclosed fields, which continued from the prehistoric era.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The infield was the best land, close to housing.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was farmed continuously and most intensively, receiving most of the manure.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were usually bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for largely for oats.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was fertilised from the overnight folding of cattle in the summer and was often left fallow to recover its fertility.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In fertile regions the infield could be extensive, but in the uplands it might be small, surrounded by large amounts of outfield.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In coastal areas fertiliser included seaweed and around the major burghs urban refuse was used.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Yields were fairly low, often around three times the quantity of seed sown, although they could reach twice that yield on some infields.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The main unit of land measurement in Scotland was the *davoch* (i.e.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This unit is also known as the "Scottish ploughgate".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In English-speaking Lothian, it was simply a ploughgate.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have measured about 104 acres (0.42 km2), divided into 4 *raths* or eight *oxgangs*, the area that eight oxen were said to be able to plough in one year.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the fourteenth century most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, who were usually known as husbandmen or bonders.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The average amount of land used by a husbandman in Scotland, known as a husbandland, was 26 acres, or 2 oxgangs.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They would also have had a share of hay meadow and common pasture.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Below the husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants, were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Farms also might have grassmen, who had rights only to grazing.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Pasture was often accessed by shieling-grounds, with shelters made of stone or turf, used for the grazing of cattle in summer.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These would often be distant from the main settlements in the Lowlands, but might be relatively close in the more remote Highlands.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs, were a ridge and furrow pattern, similar to that used in parts of England, with alternating "runs" (furrows) and "rigs" (ridges).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land, helping to offset some of the problems of extreme weather conditions.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective on heavy soils and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were usually pulled by a team of eight oxen, which would have taken four men to operate and only covered half an acre a day.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Key crops included kale (for both humans and animals), and hemp and flax for cloth production.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised primarily for meat.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Towards the end of the period average temperatures began to reduce again, with the cooler and wetter conditions of the Little Ice Age limiting the extent of arable agriculture, particularly in the Highlands.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The early modern era saw the impact of the Little Ice Age, which peaked towards the end of the seventeenth century.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The closing decade of the seventeenth century saw a slump, followed by four years of failed harvests, in what is known as the "seven ill years", but these shortages would be the last of their kind.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] After the Union of 1707 there was a conscious attempt to improve agriculture among the gentry and nobility.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Introductions included haymaking, the English plough, new crops, crop rotation and encloses were introduced.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The resulting Lowland Clearances saw hundreds of thousands of cottars and tenant farmers from central and southern Scotland lose access to land and either become landless agricultural workers or emigrate to the growing industrial cities or elsewhere.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The later Highland Clearances involved the eviction of many traditional tenants as lands were enclosed, principally for sheep farming.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the first phase, many Highlanders were relocated as crofters, living on very small rented farms which required other employment to be found.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the twentieth century Scottish agriculture became more susceptible to world markets.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There were dramatic price rises in the First World War, but a slump in the 1920s and 1930s, followed by more rises in World War II.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In 1947 annual price reviews were introduced in an attempt to stabilise the market.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was a drive in UK agriculture to greater production until the late 1970s, resulting in intensive farming.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was increasing mechanisation and farming became less labour-intensive.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] UK membership of the European Economic Community from 1972 began a change in orientation for Scottish farming.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some sectors became viable only with subsidies.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A series of reforms to the CAP from the 1990s attempted to control over-production, limit incentives for intensive farming and mitigate environmental damage.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A dual farm structure has emerged with agriculture divided between large commercial farms and small pluralised and diversified holdings.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Roughly 79 per cent of Scotland’s total land area is under agricultural production.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Cereals accounted for 78 per cent of cropped land area (not total farmed area), while livestock numbers have been falling in recent years.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Around 15 per cent of the total land area of Scotland is forested, most in public ownership controlled by the Forestry Commission.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Total income from farming has been rising since the turn of the millennium.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Aquaculture production is focused on the West and North of the country.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some farm businesses rely on sources of income other than from farming.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scottish agriculture employs around 1.5 per cent of the workforce and contributes to around 1 per cent of the Scottish economy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The defining factor in the geography of Scotland is the distinction between the Highlands and Islands in the north and west and the Lowlands in the south and east.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Highlands are further divided into the Northwest Highlands and the Grampian Mountains by the fault line of the Great Glen.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Lowlands are divided into the fertile belt of the Central Lowlands and the higher terrain of the Southern Uplands, which included the Cheviot Hills, over which the border with England runs.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Central Lowland belt averages about 50 miles in width, and contains most of the good quality agricultural land.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland is half the size of England and Wales in area, but with its many inlets, islands and inland lochs, it has roughly the same amount of coastline at 4,000 miles.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Only a fifth of Scotland is less than 60 metres above sea level.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland's soils are diverse for a relatively small country due to the variation in geology, topography, climate, altitude and land use history.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There are very productive arable soils in the east of the country, including some of the most productive for wheat and barley of anywhere in the world.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland's soils differ from much of the rest of the UK and Europe and they provide valuable habitats for wildlife and flora.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] They are largely naturally acidic in nature with high concentrations of organic carbon.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] They are predominantly coarse textured and often exhibit poor drainage.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The climate of Scotland is temperate and very changeable, but rarely extreme.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland is warmed by the North Atlantic Drift and given the northerly location of the country, experiences much milder conditions than areas on similar latitudes.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Average temperatures are lower than in the rest of Great Britain.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Western coastal areas of Scotland are warmer than the east and inland areas, due to the influence of the Atlantic currents, and the colder surface temperatures of the North Sea.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Rainfall totals vary widely across Scotland—the western highlands of Scotland are one of the wettest places in the UK with annual rainfall up to 4,577 mm (180.2 in).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In comparison, much of eastern Scotland receives less than 870 mm (34.3 in) annually; lying in the rain shadow of the western uplands.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Annual average sunshine totals vary from as little as 711–1140 hours in the Highlands and the north-west up to 1471–1540 hours on the extreme eastern and south-western coasts.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Wind prevails from the south-west, bringing warm, wet and unstable air from the Atlantic.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The windiest areas of Scotland are in the north and west, with parts of the Outer Hebrides, Orkney and Shetland experiencing over 30 days with gales per year.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Vigorous Atlantic depressions, also known as European windstorms, are a common feature of the autumn and winter in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Mesolithic hunter-gatherer encampments formed the first known settlements in Scotland around 8500 BCE.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] These were highly mobile boat-using people making tools from bone, stone and antlers.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the Neolithic period, around 6,000 years ago, there is evidence of permanent settlements and farming.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Archaeological evidence indicates that the two main sources of food were grain and cow's milk.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] From the beginning of the Bronze Age, about 2000 BCE, arable land spread at the expense of forest.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] From the Iron Age, beginning in the seventh century BCE, there is evidence of hill forts in southern Scotland that are associated with cultivation ridges and terraces.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Souterrains, small underground constructions, may have been for storing perishable agricultural products.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Aerial photography reveals extensive prehistoric field systems that underlie existing boundaries in some Lowland areas, suggesting that the fertile plains were already densely exploited for agriculture.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] During the period of Roman occupation there was re-growth of birch, oak and hazel for five centuries, suggesting a decline of population and agriculture.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The early Middle Ages were a period of climate deterioration resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Farming was based around a single homestead or a small cluster of three or four homes, each probably containing a nuclear family.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than corn (here meaning wheat) and cattle were the most important domesticated animal.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] As feudal distinctions declined in the early modern era, the barons and tenants-in-chief merged to form a new identifiable group, the lairds.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] With the substantial landholders of the yeomen, these heritors were the major landholding orders.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Those with property rights included husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Many young people, both male and female, left home to become domestic and agricultural servants.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The early modern era also saw the impact of the Little Ice Age, of colder and wetter weather, which peaked towards the end of the seventeenth century.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Almost half the years in the second half of the sixteenth century saw local or national scarcity, necessitating the shipping of large quantities of grain from the Baltic.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the early seventeenth century famine was relatively common, with four periods of famine prices between 1620 and 1625.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The English invasions of the 1640s had a profound impact on the Scottish economy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Under the Commonwealth, the country was relatively highly taxed, but gained access to English markets.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] After the Restoration the formal frontier with England was re-established, along with its customs duties.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Economic conditions were generally favourable from 1660 to 1688, as land owners promoted better tillage and cattle-raising.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The closing decade of the seventeenth century there was a slump in trade with the Baltic and France and changes in the Scottish cattle trade, followed by four years of failed harvests (1695, 1696 and 1698-9), known as the "seven ill years".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The shortages of the 1690s would be the last of their kind.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Increasing contacts with England after the Union of 1707 led to a conscious attempt to improve agriculture among the gentry and nobility.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The English plough was introduced and foreign grasses, the sowing of rye grass and clover.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Turnips and cabbages were introduced, lands enclosed and marshes drained, lime was put down to combat soil acidity, roads built and woods planted.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Drilling and sowing and crop rotation were introduced.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The introduction of the potato to Scotland in 1739 provided a crop with a high yield, producing 3 to 5 times more calories per acre than a cereal crop.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Enclosures began to displace the run rig system.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The first result of these changes were the Lowland Clearances.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The botanist John Hope complained about British naturalists who were enthusiastically exploring the landscape of colonial America while "absolutely inattentive to the natural productions of our native country".
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] He founded the Society for the Importation of Foreign Seeds and Plants pursuing, as Carl Linnaeus did in Lapland, the adaptation of valuable cash crop plants to the Highlands.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Agricultural improvement spread north and west, mostly over the period 1760 to 1850 as the Highland Clearances.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Many farming tenants were evicted and offered tenancies in crofting communities, with their former possessions converted into large-scale sheep farms.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Crofts were intended to be too small to support the occupants, so forcing them to work in other industries, such as fishing, quarrying or kelping.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the 1840 and 1850s Scotland suffered its last major subsistence crisis, when the potato blight that caused the Great Famine of Ireland reached the Highlands in 1846.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] This gave rise to the second phase of the Highland clearances, when landlords provided assisted passages for their tenants to emigrate in a desperate effort to rid themselves of a redundant population that was dependent on famine relief.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the twentieth century Scottish agriculture became susceptible to the ups and downs of world markets.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] After World War II there was a drive in UK agriculture to greater production until the late 1970s, resulting in intensive farming.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] More areas of marginal land were brought into production.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was increasing mechanisation of Scottish agriculture and farming became less labour-intensive.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The UK membership of the European Economic Community (later the European Union) in 1972 began a change in orientation for Scottish farming.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some sectors, particularly hill sheep farming, became viable only with subsidies.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A dual farm structure emerged, with agriculture divided between large commercial farms and small pluralised and diversified holdings.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] At the time of the June 2013 agricultural census the total area of agricultural holdings in Scotland was 5.6 million hectares, equal to 73 per cent of Scotland’s total land area.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Just over half of this was rough grazing, with about a quarter taken up by grass, and about ten per cent used for crops or left fallow.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The remainder was made up of woodland, ponds, yards or other uses.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was a further 580,000 hectares of common grazing, which if included made the total area 6.2 million hectares, or 79 per cent of Scotland’s total land area.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Because of the persistence of feudalism and the land enclosures of the nineteenth century, the ownership of most land is concentrated in relatively few hands (some 350 people own about half the land).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] As a result, in 2003 the Scottish Parliament passed Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 that empowered tenant farmers and communities to purchase land even if the landlord did not want to sell.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In June 2013, of crops grown in Scotland (excluding grass), cereals accounted for 78 per cent of the land area, with nearly three-quarters of that being barley (340,000 hectares).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Wheat was also significant (87,000 hectares), along with oilseed rape (34,000 hectares), oats (32,000 hectares) and potatoes (29,000 hectares).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Amongst fruit and vegetables, a total of 911 hectares of strawberries were grown, mainly under cover, which was the largest source of income amongst horticulture crops.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The major areas of cereal production were Grampian, Tayside, Borders, Lothian and Fife.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Livestock numbers have been falling in recent years.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The trend began at the turn of the millennium in the case of pigs and sheep and dates to the mid-1970s in the case of cattle.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In June 2013 there were 6.6 million sheep, 1.8 million cattle and 308,000 pigs, the lowest numbers since the 1940 and 1950s.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Poultry numbers have tended to fluctuate over the last 25 years, but were down to 14.2 million in 2013.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] About 13,340 km2 of land in Scotland is forested representing around 15 per cent of the total land area of Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The majority of forests are in public ownership, with forestry policy being controlled by the Forestry Commission.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The biggest plantations and timber resources are to be found in Dumfries and Galloway, Tayside, Argyll and the area governed by Highland Council.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The economic activities generated by forestry in Scotland include planting and harvesting as well as sawmilling, the production of pulp and paper and the manufacture of higher value goods.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Forests, especially those surrounding populated areas in Central Scotland also provide a recreation resource.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Total income from farming (TIFF) has been rising since the turn of the millennium.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] It was estimated at £700 million in 2012, being made up of £2.9 billion in outputs and £570 million in support payments, offset by £2.8 billion in costs.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The initial estimate of TIFF for 2013 was £830 million, an increase largely linked to the improved weather.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] TIFF per annual work unit increased to £31,000, similar to the value in 2011.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The total output of aquaculture was estimated in 2011 at around £434 million per year, including around £412 million for farmed Atlantic salmon, £14.34 million for rainbow trout and £7.7 million for shellfish.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Brown trout, sea trout, halibut and Arctic charr are also farmed in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some farm businesses rely on sources of income other than from farming, including contracting work, hosting mobile phone masts, tourism and recreation and financial support from grants and subsidies.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Analysis of the Farm Accounts Survey suggests that, excluding support from grants and subsidies, the average farm made a loss of £16,000 in 2012.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] However, calculations from TIFF suggest that, excluding support, the sector still made a small profit.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Government figures indicate that in 2013 Scottish agriculture employed around 1.5 per cent of the workforce and contributes around 1 per cent of the Scottish economy.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the Highlands and Islands, around 10 per cent of the workforce are engaged in agriculture and livestock products contribute around 70 per cent of the output.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The West of Scotland Agricultural College formed in 1899, the East of Scotland Agricultural College in 1901, and the North of Scotland Agricultural College in 1904; these colleges amalgamated to form the Scottish Agricultural College in 1990.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Site-specific nature conservations began in the UK with the creation of the Nature Conservancy in 1948, which later became the Nature Conservancy Council (NCC).
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] It moved from a research-based advisory group to become a campaigning body.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The 1949 National Parks and Access to the Countryside Act excluded Scotland, but introduced the concept of Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI), which were to become a key part of managing nature conservation.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A Countryside Commission Scotland (CSS) was established under the Countryside Scotland Act, 1967.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The NCC was broken up in 1991 and in Scotland was merged with CSS to produce Scottish Natural Heritage (SNH), under a UK-wide Joint Nature Conservation Committee.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] SNH has a remit for both land and nature conservation and a responsibility towards sustainability and to the consideration of the needs of the Scottish people.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In Scotland, a right of way is a route over which the public has been able to pass unhindered for at least 20 years.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The route must link two "public places", such as villages, churches or roads.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Unlike in England and Wales there is no obligation on Scottish local authorities to signpost or mark a right of way.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] However, the charity Scotways, formed in 1845 to protect rights of way, records and signs the routes.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 gives everyone statutory access rights to most land and inland water in Scotland, to non-motorized traffic, making the existence of rights of way less important in terms of access to land in Scotland.
[src:a-people-s-history-of-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Certain categories of land are excluded from this presumption of open access, such as railway land, airfields and private gardens.
